Presenting Problem / Chief Complaint: The patient has been feeling mostly okay, with some ups and downs, and has expressed feelings of anxiety regarding their job search.
History of Present Illness (HPI): The patient has sent out a few resumes, which felt relieving but also nerve-wracking. They worry about their qualifications and tend to shut down when feeling inadequate. They recognize the need to remind themselves of their strengths to combat self-doubt.
Psychosocial History: The patient has maintained contact with their mother, who expresses concern about their job search. They feel mostly supported but believe their mother may not fully understand the industry.
Physiological Observations: The patient has been experiencing sleep issues and weird dreams, which affect their focus. They have attempted deep breathing exercises before bed but struggle with consistency.
Current Functional Status: The patient is willing to set reminders for self-care practices like deep breathing to improve their sleep.
Progress Evaluation: The patient is making progress by sending out resumes and recognizing their strengths, but they still face challenges with anxiety and sleep.
Therapeutic Interventions: The patient plans to create a list of strengths and accomplishments to refer to when feeling self-doubt. They will also work on consistency with deep breathing exercises.
Next Steps: The patient aims to continue sending out resumes, work on their strengths list, and practice deep breathing before bed.
